-- The Tier-2 Z3 measure check for @total (SPEC §12.6, north-star §3.3) — the
-- `proof.terminates` fall-through totality-design §3 promised. When the
-- structural check is a fn's ONLY failure, Z3 proves per recursive call that
-- one argument position UNIT-DECREASES a floored measure (facts ⟹ arg ≤ n−1
-- and n ≥ 0, refuted over the reals). `halve` is Tier 1's pinned valve case:
-- n/2 is no structural decrease, but `if n < 2` proves n ≥ 2 ⟹ n/2 ≤ n − 1.
-- `shrink` decreases by a NON-CONSTANT k — beyond any structural check — and
-- proves from the k >= 1 guard. Note the guards earn the proof: `if n <= 0`
-- would NOT prove halve (Z3's counterexample is n = 1).
-- Expected: clean; runs.
@edition "2026.6"

@total
def halve(n: Number): Number
  if n < 2 then 0 else 1 + halve(n / 2)

@total
def shrink(n: Number, k: Number): Number
  if n <= 0 then 0
  else if k < 1 then 0
  else 1 + shrink(n - k, k)

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(halve(40))
  println(shrink(10, 3))
  println(shrink(10, 0.5))
